subSubSection.paragraph:
Descriptive notes.
Head-body 4-8-8:-1 cm (mean: 7-2 cm for males and 6-4 cm for females), tail 5.3-7.1 cm (mean: 6-2 cm for males and 6 cm for females); weight 6-14 g (mean: 10 g for males and 9 g for females). There is subtle sexual dimorphism for size. The Southern Ningaui can be distinguished from the Pilbara Ningaui (
N. timealeyi
) by its hindfoot, which has pads on rear of sole that are smaller and less obvious. The Southern Ningaui and the Wongai Ningaui (
NN. ridei
) are apparently sisters, based on genetic phylogenies. They are very similar morphologically; only skull characters can separate them. The Southern Ningaui has relatively smaller auditory bullae (ear bones) than the Wongai Ningaui.
